:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-EROOM foKNLL pf-199_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-dNsUpz eAuVCY pf-194_ pf-text-1"><strong>Reducing contamination risk</strong> - The one-way valve or filter pad prevents the rescuer from contacting the patient’s saliva, blood, or other fluids.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-dNsUpz eAuVCY pf-196_ pf-text-1"><strong>Encouraging quick action</strong> - Many people hesitate to perform mouth-to-mouth resuscitation, even when urgently needed, due to the fear of contamination. Having a face shield on hand eliminates this concern and helps rescuers focus on delivering life-saving care.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-dNsUpz eAuVCY pf-198_ pf-text-1"><strong>Practical for all skill levels</strong> - Whether you’re a seasoned first aider or a complete beginner, CPR face shields are easy to use. They ensure that you can confidently perform rescue breaths in a safe and sanitary manner.</li></ul></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-8677" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-dxcExB gjNMyZ pf-40_ pf-color-scheme-1 pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide pf-hide"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-kqGpvY OSjcf"><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-41_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:8px;--s-sm:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-lnPyOc gUmbDa pf-42_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-brPMkR cnEYUf pf-43_ pf-heading-1-h3">How to use a CPR face shield</h3><p class="sc-iMWBWc laPXAE pf-45_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The face shield shown in the image is a resuscitation face shield used during mouth-to-mouth resuscitation to provide personal protection against cross-contamination. Here’s a step-by-step guide on how to use it:</p><div data-pf-type="Slideshow" cl